<paragraph id="3C485D0DFFE6FF82E5D600E53077FE86" blockId="3.[151,1437,152,655]" pageId="3" pageNumber="286">
Male palps (
<figureCitation id="A4CC4188FFE6FF82E44000E5339CFF26" box="[337,436,152,175]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1813,1835]" captionTargetBox="[154,1435,194,1793]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[151,1435,194,1793]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Histopona breviemboli sp. n., male holotype. 1. Habitus, dorsal view; 2. Habitus, ventral view; 3 – 5. Male palp, prolateral, ventral and retrolateral view. Scale lines: 2.0 — 1, 2; 0.2 — 3 – 5." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847460/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="286">Figs 3–5</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="A4CC4188FFE6FF82E4D300E533C7FF26" box="[450,495,152,175]" captionStart="FIGURES 6 – 8" captionStartId="2.[151,258,1149,1171]" captionTargetBox="[170,1421,203,1114]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,191,1128]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 6 – 8. Histopona breviemboli sp. n., male paratype. 6 – 8. Male palp, prolateral, ventral and retrolateral view. Scale lines: 0.2." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/847462/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="286">6–8</figureCitation>
): With retrolateral tibial and retrolateral patellar apophyses. Tibial apophysis with no branches, pointed at the end. Patellar apophysis short and simple. Bulbus: Embolus very short (not typical for 
<taxonomicName id="FBF7268EFFE6FF82E58600A5332EFF66" authorityName="Dimitrov &amp; Deltshev &amp; Lazarov" authorityYear="2017" box="[151,262,216,239]" class="Arachnida" family="Agelenidae" genus="Histopona" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="3" pageNumber="286" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0E83811FFFE6FF82E58600A5332EFF66" box="[151,262,216,239]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="286">Histopona</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Radix thorn-like, very similar in shape to the embolus. At a glance, it looks like that the embolus is forked. Both embolus and radix go into conductor.
</paragraph>
